g themselves in terms of their country of destination alone, second-generation Nigerians define themselves in complicated ways that balance racial status, a diasporic Nigerian ethnicity, a pan-African identity, and identification with fellow immigrants. Based on over 150 interviews, Beyond Expectations seeks to understand how race, ethnicity, and class shape identity and how globalization, transnationalism, and national context inform sense of self.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aChildren of immigrantszGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aChildren of immigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aNigerianszGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aNigerianszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aafrican american.  aafrican immigrants.  ablack identity.  acaribbean.  aemigration.  aethnicity.  aglobalization.  aidentity.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration.  aknow yourself.  anational identity.  anigeria.  anigerian american.  anigerian descent.  anigerian identity.  apan african.  arace.  aracial identity.  aracism.  asecond generation.  aself identity.  asocial science.  atransnationalism.  atrue story.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029232140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965881423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965881/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles